\pard\keepn\widctlpar\s1\sb240\sa60\sl252\slmult1\qc\cf1\kerning32\b\f0\fs32 Steem 4.0.2 release notes\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\s1\sb240\sa60\sl252\slmult1\f1 Atari ST\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\kerning0\b0\f2\fs22 The Atari ST was a legendary 16bit computer of the Eighties.\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\s1\sb240\sa60\sl252\slmult1\cf1\kerning32\b\f1\fs32 Steem Engine, by Anthony & Russell Hayward\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\kerning0\b0\f2\fs22 Steem is a legendary Atari ST emulator for the PC, both accurate and easy to use thanks to its great user interface.\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\s2\sb240\sa60\sl252\slmult1\cf1\b\i\f1\fs28 Steem SSE\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\b0\i0\f2\fs22 Steem SSE stands for \i ST Enhanced EMulator Sensei Software Edition\i0 . It is an updated version of Steem. Some say an improvement, some say it's worse!\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\s2\sb240\sa60\sl252\slmult1\cf1\b\i\f1\fs28 Licence\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\b0\i0\f2\fs22 Steem is free open source software. The licence is GPL3 as chosen by Steem authors.\par

\pard\keepn\widctlpar\s1\sb240\sa60\sl252\slmult1\cf1\kerning32\b\f1\fs32 Installation\par

\pard\widctlpar\sa160\sl252\slmult1\cf0\kerning0\b0\f2\fs22 Extract files to a folder of your choice. There's no setup program.\par
\lang2057 When you run a Steem SSE build for the first time, based on the file name, it proposes to add a link to the new version in your start menu if you care about that\f3\lang6153 , unless NoIntro is specified (see manual). \f2\lang2057 You may skip everything if Steem was already installed (but then you need to start a second time).\par
\cf1\kerning32\b\f1\fs32\lang6153 v4.0.2 Notices\par
\cf0\kerning0\b0\f2\fs22\lang2057 So that 32bit and 64bit versions of Steem can cohabit in the same directory, all the plugins can be stored in a \i plugins32\i0  or \i plugins64\i0  folder, it's the first place where Steem will look. After that, it looks in a \i plugins\i0  folder, then, for DLL files, in a folder with the same name as the DLL (pasti, FreeImage...). Finally in Steem's main directory.\par
\cf1\kerning32\b\f1\fs32\lang6153 v4.0.2 Features\par

\pard\widctlpar\sl276\slmult1\cf0\kerning0\f4\fs24\lang2057 Keyboard Language\par
\b0\f2\fs22 In keyboard options, the last choice in the language list, \i Mapping file\i0 , allows you to select an ini file that contains key mappings. Examples are included for the German and French keyboards. The format is simple, you just need to know the ST keys, that's why a graphic is also included. The point of the feature is to allow you to create your own mapping in case you're not satisfied with Steem's hardcoded mapping.\par
\par
\b\f4\fs24 High Density Disks\par
\b0\f2\fs22 Steem should better handle 1.44MB disk images. It's a hack in as much as regular STs used 720 KB disks (Double Density). The Mega STE could handle high density.\par
\par
\b\f4\fs24 Memory snapshots\b0\f2\fs22\par
Better compatibility with snapshots of old Steem versions, better detection of corrupt snapshots\par
\ul Note\ulnone : memory snapshots of Steem32 and Steem64 are not compatible!\par
\par
\b\f4\fs24 Option fast blitter\par
\b0\f2\fs22 No timing cycles are counted for blitter operation. It's a hack available on the ST video page.\b\f1\fs24\lang6153\par

